answers.body_markdown:
You should have one pivot table `autoservice_service`.

In your Service Models
```
public function autoServices(){
  $this-&gt;belongsToMany(&#39;App\AutoService&#39;);
}
```
In your Master model
```
public function autoServices(){
  $this-&gt;hasMany(&#39;App\AutoService&#39;);
}
```
In your AutoService model
```
public function services(){
  $this-&gt;belongsToMany(&#39;App\Service&#39;);
}
public function masters(){
  $this-&gt;belongsTo(&#39;App\Master&#39;);
}
```
in pivot tables use then `service_id`, `master_id`, `autoservice_id`. If you want to use timestamps use method `withTimestamps()` (f.e. `$this-&gt;belongsToMany(&#39;App\Master&#39;)-&gt;withTimestamps();`

EDIT: 
If you want to make a relationship between Master and Service in which one Master can have multiple services and vice versa, you should make another pivot table `master_service`. In `Service` model:
```
public function masters(){
   return $this-&gt;belongsToMany(&#39;App\Master&#39;);
}
```
and in `Master` model:
```
public function services(){
   return $this-&gt;belongsToMany(&#39;App\Service&#39;);
}
```
now you&#39;re able to check what master does, examples
```
1) Services of master
App\Master::find($id)-&gt;services();
2) Which masters do service
App\Service::find($id)-&gt;masters();
```

The other workaround is that you can add another foreign key in your pivot table, and then use `-&gt;withPivot(&#39;column1&#39;, &#39;column2&#39;)`.

